trusts will be offered a premium of 25% on top of the tariff they receive for providing treatment if they report that it was given to a citizen of one of the 27 other EU member states.</p><p>Hunt said that the move would \"more than pay for itself\" because the NHS is able to reclaim the cost of treatment from other member states under long-standing reciprocal arrangements through the use of a European Health Insurance Card (Ehic).</p><p>At present, the UK pays other EU countries more than £800m a year to cover the cost of Britons receiving healthcare on holidays and other visits abroad, but receives back only £29m for nationals of the EU and European Economic Area treated here.</p><p>When patients from outside Europe are included, the NHS takes in only £73m of the £500m a year believed to be due, which is around 16% of the total, said Hunt.</p><p>Speaking at a Westminster lunch, Hunt said the shortfall stemmed from the fact that recording treatment of foreign nationals represents an extra administrative burden for hospitals and surgeries, but they receive the same payments under the NHS tariff scheme as they would if the patient was British.</p><p>Hunt said: \"Independent research suggests there is about half a billion quid in money we should be collecting from international visitors who use the NHS. We only collect around 16% of that money – £73m a year.</p><p>\"I have no problem whatsoever with foreigners using our NHS, as long as they contribute to it either through taxes or through paying charges. We need to be much better at collecting that revenue.\"</p><p>Hunt added: \"We should be receiving a lot more money, but we don't. The reason is because trusts have no financial incentive to report someone as an EU visitor. It's an extra complication and if they don't report it they get the NHS tariff.</p><p>\"Today, we are announcing a premium on the tariff for trusts who report EU visitors using their services, to pay for the extra administrative costs and to create financial incentives so we get proper reporting and we get the money.</p><p>\"My target is that by this and subsequent measures we will announce for non-EU visitors, we will raise around half a billion pounds a year to pay for additional doctors and nurses on the frontline.\"</p><p>The new 125% tariff for treating EU nationals will be available to NHS trusts in England.</p>","headline":"NHS trusts offered incentives to recoup overseas patient costs","trailText":"Trusts to receive premium on tariff for treating foreign visitors, which will help recover £500m each year, says Jeremy Hunt","newspaperPageNumber":"14","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/6/17/1403023756459/NHS-doctor-fills-out-pape-003.jpg","wordcount":"433","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"439711205","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"9178944","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Press Association","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-06-18T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2111608","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-06-20T17:10:02Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/jun/17/nhs-trusts-incentives-overseas-patient-costs","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/society/2014/jun/17/nhs-trusts-incentives-overseas-patient-costs","tags":[{"id":"society/nhs","webTitle":"NHS","type":"keyword","sectionId":"society","sectionName":"Society","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/society/nhs","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/society/nhs","references":[]},{"id":"society/health","webTitle":"Health","type":"keyword","sectionId":"society","sectionName":"Society","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/society/health","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/society/health","references":[]},{"id":"society/policy","webTitle":"Public services policy","type":"keyword","sectionId":"society","sectionName":"Society","we